<DOC><DOCNO> AP880803-0274 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-88 1259EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-AluminumTalks     08-03 0303</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Aluminum Talks,0313</SECOND><HEAD>Early Aluminum Contract Talks Set</HEAD><DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two major unions will be looking for a shareof the aluminum industry's profits next week when they open earlynegotiations to replace contracts that expire 10 months from now.   The current two-year pacts with the United Steelworkers ofAmerica and the Aluminum, Brick and Glass Workers InternationalUnion lowered benefits by 95 cents per hour for their members atAluminum Company of America and Reynolds Metals Co.   ``When we negotiated the current contracts in 1986, our membersmade sacrifices to help the companies over hard time,'' said GeorgeBecker, internatinal vice president of the USW. ``Now that thesecompanies are profitable again, our members deserve to share inthose gains and recover the sacrifices they made.''   Becker, who chairs the union's aluminum industry conference, wasquoted in the USW publication ``Steelabor.''   Pittsburgh-based Alcoa, the nation's largest aluminum producer,reported profits of $200.1 million, or $2.25 per share, on sales of$7.77 billion for all of 1987 and profits of $416.3 million, or$4.71 per share, on sales of $4.59 billion in the first six monthsof this year.   Reynolds of Richmond, Va., reported 1987 net earnings of $219.5million, or $4.33 per share, on sales of $4.32 billion and netearnings of $204.9 million, or $3.84 per share, on revenue of $2.65billion in the 1988 first half.   The contract talks are scheduled to begin Aug. 8 in Cincinnati.The two unions will conduct concurrent but separate negotiations.Their contracts expire May 31, 1989.   The USW said it represents more than 6,000 Alcoa workers at ninelocations in the United States and approximately 4,000 Reynoldsworkers at 21 locations in the United States and Canada.   The ABGWU represents between 6,000 and 7,000 Alcoa workers andan estimated 4,700 Reynolds workers.</TEXT></DOC>